recordSet.description: The RecordSet comprises data on protein mutations, detailing sequence identifiers, wildtype and mutated amino acids, and mutation sites. It includes structural and stability metrics such as RMSD, TM-score, SASA, and hydrophobicity. Furthermore, it evaluates energy states, aggregation propensity, and binding affinity with the ACE-2 receptor. Additional insights include expression levels, structural content, and interactions relevant to protein functionality and stability. These comprehensive metrics are critical for assessing the impact of mutations on protein structure, stability, and binding interactions, essential for ACE-2 binding and RBD expression predictions.

recordSet.description: The RecordSet comprises extensive protein mutation data, detailing each mutation's sequence identifier, wildtype and mutated amino acids, and mutation sites. It includes quantitative metrics such as Root Mean Square Deviation (RMSD), TM-Score, Solvent Accessible Surface Area (SASA), and binding energy. Moreover, it provides scores for hydrophobicity, protein interaction, and post-translational modifications. Energy dynamics, expression levels, and their changes are documented, alongside confidence scores for binding and expression predictions. This dataset is critical for analyzing protein structural and functional changes, particularly in relation to ACE-2 binding and RBD expression.

methodSection.name: Study Design
methodSection.description: The methodological foundation of this study was established through a structured, multi-phase design focused on the systematic generation and analysis of structural and empirical features derived from SARS-CoV-2 spike protein variants.

step.name: Define project goals and research context
step.description: The research was conducted to investigate whether the structural consequences of amino acid substitutions in the RBD of the SARS-CoV-2 spike protein could be leveraged to predict empirical properties associated with viral fitness.

step.name: Select subdomain of interest based on computational feasibility and expert consultation
step.description: Narrowed focus to the ACE-2 RBD due to computational constraints and its critical role in host receptor binding.

step.name: Determine mutational space for RBD variants
step.description: Defined mutational space using a k-step approach around the Wuhan-Hu-1 reference, generating 1-step and 2-step variant sequences.

step.name: Define sequence categories and control sets
step.description: Classified sequences into five subsets to support different experimental goals, including scalability testing, domain validation, empirical controls, and structural benchmarking.

methodSection.name: Variant Sequence Generation
methodSection.description: Describes the procedures used to generate theoretical and empirical variant sequences of the SARS-CoV-2 RBD domain for downstream structural modeling.

step.name: Prepare reference sequence of the ACE-2 RBD domain
step.description: Selected the 195-residue ACE-2 RBD domain from the Wuhan-Hu-1 strain as the reference sequence, extracted from PDB 6M0J.

step.name: Generate 1-step and 2-step theoretical mutational variants using ViralMutations.py
step.description: Used ViralMutations.py to generate all single (1-step) and double (2-step) amino acid substitutions from the RBD reference sequence.

substep.name: Generate 1-Step Variants
substep.description: To generate 1-step variants, the script substituted each residue in the reference sequence with all 19 alternative amino acids, resulting in a total of 3,705 unique single-mutant sequences.

substep.name: Generate 2-Step Variants
substep.description: To generate 2-step variants, all possible pairwise combinations of non-identical residues and non-repeating positions were computed, yielding a total of 6,828,315 unique double-mutant sequences.

substep.name: Save Variant FASTA Entries
substep.description: The script also supported the generation of subsets or targeted variants, though these were not used in the primary dataset described here. All generated sequences were saved in individual FASTA entries, each labeled with a unique sequence identifier reflecting its mutation(s).

step.name: Curate and categorize sequence subsets
step.description: Organized all theoretical and reference sequences into five subsets, each serving distinct roles in model development and validation.

substep.name: Subset for Scalability Testing
substep.description: The first subset comprised 72 sequences, selected to test the scalability of structure prediction tools across increasing sequence lengths. These included random segments extracted from the full spike protein, ranging from 10 to 1273 amino acids.

substep.name: Validation Subset (Spike & RBD)
substep.description: The second subset included only two sequences: the full-length 1273-residue spike protein and the 195-residue RBD, used to validate the independence of the domain-based modeling approach.

substep.name: Primary Mutational Variants
substep.description: The third and principal subset consisted of the 1-step and 2-step mutational variants generated in Step 2.2.

substep.name: Verify FASTA Formatting
substep.description: All FASTA files were verified for formatting consistency and completeness before being passed to structure prediction tools.

step.name: Compile observed variant sequences and control sequences
step.description: Gathered empirical sequences from clinical isolates and experimental structures from PDB to serve as validation and benchmarking controls.

substep.name: Collect Empirical Variants
substep.description: The fourth subset comprised ACE-2 RBD sequences of SARS-CoV-2 variants observed in human populations. These included clinical isolates from all major Variants of Concern, from Alpha to the most recent Omicron lineages.

substep.name: Collect PDB Control Structures
substep.description: The fifth subset was constructed by collecting 890 spike glycoprotein sequences from the Protein Data Bank. All sequences were selected to be ≤1278 residues in length and to have corresponding experimentally validated structures, determined by X-ray crystallography or Cryo-EM. These control sequences provided essential ground truth comparisons for evaluating the accuracy of predicted structures.

methodSection.name: Protein Structure Prediction
methodSection.description: Describes computational infrastructure and methodology used to predict 3D protein structures for all RBD variant sequences using AlphaFold-2, ESMFold, and AlphaFold-Pulldown.

step.name: Configure and prepare computational infrastructure
step.description: Established distributed HPC environment with Snellius Supercomputer, local workstation, and Research Drive cloud storage for scalable structure prediction.

substep.name: Use Snellius Supercomputer
substep.description: The Snellius Supercomputer, a high-performance computing (HPC) system managed with Slurm and capable of 14 petaflops/s, was used for all GPU-accelerated structure prediction tasks.

substep.name: Local Workstation Job Testing
substep.description: The local workstation was used to write, test, and submit job scripts using SBATCH. Interactive jobs on Snellius were used to validate task configuration before batch submission.

substep.name: Setup Research Drive Storage
substep.description: A 2TB Research Drive instance, synchronized using OwnCloud, was used to store structure prediction results and provide shared access to project members.

step.name: Run AlphaFold-2 for structure prediction
step.description: Used AlphaFold-2 v2.3.1 to predict structures of 1-step variants and control sequences, generating 3D models with confidence metrics.

substep.name: Download AlphaFold Databases
substep.description: All required AlphaFold databases were pre-downloaded and stored locally on the CPU partition of Snellius. These included BFD, MGnify, PDB70, UniRef30, UniRef90, and the full PDB, amounting to 2.62 TB of reference data.

substep.name: Compute MSAs & Template Search
substep.description: For each input sequence, the system computed multiple sequence alignments (MSAs) using JackHMmer and HHblits, followed by a structure template search using HHSearch.

substep.name: Generate Sequence Representations
substep.description: The Evoformer module processed the MSAs and templates to generate sequence-pair representations, which were used by the Structure Module to output 3D coordinates.

substep.name: Generate Ranked Models
substep.description: Five ranked structural models were generated for each sequence, with associated confidence metrics, including pLDDT and TM-score.

substep.name: Store Structure Outputs
substep.description: Outputs for each run included the predicted 3D structure files (PDB), MSAs, template files, and a features.pkl file containing the input features.

step.name: Run ESMFold for structure prediction
step.description: Performed single-sequence structure prediction using ESMFold with transformer-based architecture trained on UniRef50.

substep.name: Deploy ESMFold on GPU
substep.description: ESMFold was deployed on the GPU partition of Snellius, requiring a compatible NVIDIA GPU with CUDA version ≥11.3 and PyTorch 1.11.

substep.name: Generate ESMFold Prediction
substep.description: For each sequence, ESMFold produced a single deterministic prediction based on a pre-trained 15B-parameter language model (ESM-2).

substep.name: Store ESMFold Outputs
substep.description: Output files included the predicted 3D structure (PDB) and associated confidence scores. No MSA or template files were generated.

step.name: Run AlphaFold-Pulldown for multimeric predictions
step.description: Used AlphaFold-Pulldown to model multimeric complexes and compute interface features between RBD variants and ACE-2.

substep.name: Reuse AF2 Features for Pulldown
substep.description: The features.pkl files from AlphaFold-2 runs were used as input to AF-PD, eliminating the need to regenerate MSAs.

substep.name: Execute Pulldown Mode
substep.description: The pulldown mode of AF-PD was executed via its command-line interface to predict interactions between the ACE-2 RBD and the human ACE-2 enzyme.

substep.name: Optimize AF-PD Workflow
substep.description: The AF-PD workflow separated CPU-based and GPU-based steps to optimize performance.

substep.name: Store AF-PD Outputs
substep.description: Output files included predicted multimer structures, interface confidence scores (ipTM, pDockQ, mpDockQ), and feature logs detailing residue-residue interactions, interface energy estimates, and solvation metrics.

step.name: Manage outputs and store predicted structures
step.description: Archived all prediction outputs (PDB, MSA, features.pkl, metadata) to structured storage on the SURF Research Drive for downstream analysis.

substep.name: Record AF2/AF-PD File Sizes
substep.description: AlphaFold output files were approximately 97.1 MB per sequence, while AF-PD outputs reached up to 1.6 GB per complex.

substep.name: Record ESMFold File Sizes
substep.description: ESMFold outputs were considerably smaller, averaging 124 KB per sequence.

substep.name: Organize and Verify Outputs
substep.description: All outputs were organized by subset and labeled according to their unique sequence identifiers. File integrity was verified prior to transfer using cryptographic checksums.

methodSection.name: Structural Feature Extraction
methodSection.description: Describes the extraction of structural metrics from predicted protein models, including geometric, energetic, confidence, and bioinformatic features.

step.name: Calculate RMSD and TM-score against reference structure
step.description: Computed RMSD using the BioPython Kabsch algorithm and TM-score using tmtools for alignment-based structural similarity.

substep.name: Compute RMSD via Kabsch
substep.description: RMSD was computed using the BioPython superimposer module, which applied the Kabsch algorithm to optimally align the predicted and reference structures. The centroid of each structure was translated to the origin, and the optimal rotation matrix was determined via singular value decomposition of the covariance matrix.

substep.name: Compute TM-score
substep.description: TM-score was computed using tm_align from the tmtools Python package. The TM-score calculation included normalization based on the length of the native structure and optimized the superposition to maximize global similarity.

substep.name: Assign Structural Scores
substep.description: Each predicted structure received a corresponding RMSD value in ångströms (Å) and TM-score between 0 and 1, with higher values indicating closer structural alignment to the reference.

step.name: Compute Solvent Accessible Surface Area (SASA)
step.description: Used freesasa to calculate total surface accessibility via Lee-Richards and Shrake-Rupley approximations.

substep.name: Compute SASA via freesasa
substep.description: The freesasa Python package was used to compute SASA values using both the Lee-Richards and Shrake-Rupley approximations.

substep.name: Assign Atom Radii & Compute Area
substep.description: Atom radii were assigned using ProtOr radii from Tsai et al. (1999), and surface area was computed by simulating a spherical probe rolling over the protein surface.

substep.name: Report Total SASA
substep.description: Total SASA was computed for each structure and reported in square ångströms (Å²), allowing comparison across variants.

step.name: Calculate Electrostatic Potential using APBS and PDB2PQR
step.description: Computed electrostatic potential maps via PDB2PQR and APBS, providing insights into surface charge distributions.

substep.name: Process Structures with PDB2PQR
substep.description: Protein structures were first processed using PDB2PQR, which added missing atoms, assigned atomic charges, and converted PDB files into .pqr format.

substep.name: Solve Electrostatics with APBS
substep.description: The .pqr files were input into APBS (Adaptive Poisson-Boltzmann Solver), which numerically solved the Poisson-Boltzmann equation for biomolecular electrostatics under the PARSE force field.

substep.name: Report Electrostatic Potential
substep.description: The resulting electrostatic potential values were reported in kcal/mol/e and were used in downstream analyses to infer surface charge distributions.

step.name: Extract pLDDT and pTM/ipTM from prediction models
step.description: Extracted pLDDT scores for per-residue confidence and ipTM/pTM for interface modeling; used AlphaFold model outputs.

substep.name: Extract pLDDT Scores
substep.description: pLDDT (predicted Local Distance Difference Test) scores were extracted directly from AlphaFold-2, AlphaFold-Pulldown, and ESMFold outputs. The score, ranging from 0 to 100, provided a per-residue confidence estimate of the local atomic arrangement.

substep.name: Extract ipTM/pTM Scores
substep.description: For AlphaFold-Multimer predictions, ipTM (interface predicted TM-score) and pTM (predicted TM-score) were extracted from the model’s final outputs.

substep.name: Calculate Composite Confidence
substep.description: Composite model confidence scores were calculated using a weighted average: model confidence = 0.8 × ipTM + 0.2 × pTM, as defined in the AlphaFold-Multimer implementation.

step.name: Derive protein-protein interaction metrics using AF-PD
step.description: Calculated pDockQ, mpDockQ, interface PAE, PI-score, hydrogen bonds, salt bridges, and interface residues from multimeric complexes.

substep.name: Calculate pDockQ Score
substep.description: The pDockQ score was calculated using a sigmoidal function of plDDT and interface contact count, yielding values from 0 to 1.

substep.name: Compute mpDockQ Score
substep.description: mpDockQ (multi-partner DockQ) was computed using a variant of the lDDT score to account for multiple-chain complexes.

substep.name: Calculate Average iPAE
substep.description: The average interface Predicted Aligned Error (iPAE) was calculated by aggregating the pairwise PAE values across interface residues.

substep.name: Determine PI-Score
substep.description: The PI-Score, a support vector machine-based score trained on Cryo-EM assemblies, was used to determine whether the interface was likely native-like. Scores ranged from -2.5 to 2.5.

substep.name: Extract Additional Interface Features
substep.description: Additional interface features were extracted, including interface residue counts, numbers of hydrogen bonds and salt bridges, and geometric complementarity.

step.name: Aggregate Bio2Byte feature metrics
step.description: Used DynaMine, EFoldMine, DisoMine, and AgMata from the Bio2Byte suite to derive predictive per-residue structural features, averaged for each sequence.

substep.name: Predict Flexibility with DynaMine
substep.description: The DynaMine tool was used to predict backbone and side-chain flexibility, including indicators for secondary structure and polyproline II content.

substep.name: Identify Early Folding Regions
substep.description: EFoldMine was used to identify early folding regions that could serve as structural nucleation points.

substep.name: Predict Disordered Regions
substep.description: DisoMine predicted disordered regions based on the input sequence alone, with scores reflecting structural fluidity.

substep.name: Assess β-Aggregation Propensity
substep.description: AgMata assessed the propensity for β-aggregation, a property relevant to amyloidogenicity and potential viral pathogenesis.

substep.name: Average Bio2Byte Metrics
substep.description: As the Bio2Byte metrics were calculated per residue, each metric was averaged across all residues in the sequence to produce a single feature value per structure. These averages were then appended to the dataset as individual columns.

methodSection.name: Integration of Empirical Data
methodSection.description: Describes how deep mutational scanning data from BloomLab was integrated with the structural dataset to create supervised learning targets for binding and expression.

step.name: Extract ACE-2 binding and RBD expression values from BloomLab datasets
step.description: Retrieved log-transformed binding (KD) and expression (MFI) values for 1-step RBD variants from BloomLab deep mutational scanning experiments.

substep.name: Extract Binding Data
substep.description: The binding data consisted of log-transformed equilibrium dissociation constants (log(KD)) measured for each 1-step mutational variant. These values represented the strength of ACE-2 binding, with lower KD indicating tighter binding.

substep.name: Extract Expression Data
substep.description: Expression data consisted of log-transformed mean fluorescence intensity (log(MFI)) values, which served as a proxy for surface presentation of the RBD on cells. Higher MFI values indicated greater expression.

substep.name: Filter by Mutation Step
substep.description: Only variants corresponding to 1-step mutations from the Wuhan-Hu-1 reference sequence were included, ensuring exact alignment with the set of predicted structural variants.

step.name: Align empirical features with corresponding 1-step variant sequences
step.description: Mapped BloomLab measurements to structural records using unique sequence identifiers.

substep.name: Assign Variant Names
substep.description: Each 1-step variant sequence in the dataset was named according to its specific amino acid substitution and residue position, e.g., E152K, enabling direct lookup in the empirical dataset.

substep.name: Create Empirical Mapping Table
substep.description: A mapping table was constructed linking each sequence identifier to its corresponding binding and expression values, ensuring no mismatches or duplicates.

substep.name: Exclude Unmatched Variants
substep.description: Sequences with no corresponding empirical measurements were excluded from the supervised modeling phase. Only variants for which both structural and empirical data existed were retained.

step.name: Calculate Δ (delta) values relative to wild-type reference
step.description: Computed delta binding and delta expression values by subtracting wild-type log(KD) and log(MFI) from mutant measurements.

substep.name: Extract Wild-Type Values
substep.description: The wild-type reference values for binding and expression were extracted from the BloomLab dataset, corresponding to the unmutated Wuhan-Hu-1 RBD sequence.

substep.name: Compute Delta Binding
substep.description: For each variant, delta binding was calculated as the difference between the variant’s log(KD) value and that of the wild-type.

substep.name: Compute Delta Expression
substep.description: Similarly, delta expression was computed as the difference between the variant’s log(MFI) and the wild-type log(MFI).

substep.name: Include Delta Features
substep.description: These delta features were included in models that aimed to predict relative changes rather than absolute values, providing additional interpretability and reducing the impact of potential batch effects in experimental data collection.

methodSection.name: Machine Learning Dataset Construction
methodSection.description: Outlines how structural and empirical data were combined, standardized, and formatted into supervised learning-ready datasets for regression modeling.

step.name: Standardize and normalize structural feature columns
step.description: Used sklearn StandardScaler to standardize structural features including RMSD, TM-score, SASA, pLDDT, ipTM, pDockQ, and Bio2Byte-derived metrics.

substep.name: Load and Organize Dataset
substep.description: The dataset was loaded into memory using the pandas Python library and organized into a tabular structure, where each row represented a single variant and each column represented a structural or empirical feature.

substep.name: Standardize Features
substep.description: Structural features were standardized using the StandardScaler function from the sklearn.preprocessing module. Each feature was centered to a mean of 0 and scaled to unit variance across the dataset.

substep.name: Select Metrics for Standardization
substep.description: Structural metrics included in the standardization process were RMSD, TM-score, SASA, electrostatic potential, pLDDT, ipTM, pDockQ, and all Bio2Byte-derived sequence metrics (e.g., AgMata, DisoMine, DynaMine, and EFoldMine).

substep.name: Archive Raw Values
substep.description: Standardized values replaced raw metric values in the working dataset, and the original feature values were retained in a separate archive for traceability.

step.name: Split datasets into training and validation subsets
step.description: Applied 80/20 train-test split and 5-fold cross-validation for performance assessment. Variants with empirical data were used for supervised learning.

substep.name: Implement Train-Test Split
substep.description: An 80/20 train-test split was implemented using the train_test_split function from the sklearn.model_selection module. Stratification was not applied, as the target variables (binding and expression) were continuous and not categorical.

substep.name: Apply 5-Fold Cross-Validation
substep.description: To ensure robust performance assessment, a 5-fold cross-validation scheme was used within the training set during model training. Each fold preserved the 80/20 split internally, ensuring statistical consistency across validation runs.

substep.name: Hold Out Test Set
substep.description: The test set was held out entirely from the training process and used exclusively to assess generalization on unseen data, including variants from higher-order mutational neighborhoods (e.g., Omicron BA.1 and BA.2).

step.name: Prepare feature matrix and target vectors for regression models
step.description: Constructed feature-target datasets for both two-target (binding, expression) and four-target (plus delta features) regression tasks.

substep.name: Prepare Two-Target Dataset
substep.description: For the two-target model configuration, the feature matrix included all structural features, and the target vector consisted of binding (log(KD)) and expression (log(MFI)).

substep.name: Prepare Four-Target Dataset
substep.description: For the four-target model configuration, the target vector included binding, delta binding, expression, and delta expression. All four targets were extracted from the integrated dataset as described in Section 5.

substep.name: Ensure Consistent Target Order
substep.description: The number and order of target variables were kept fixed per model to prevent schema mismatch at inference time.

substep.name: Serialize Dataset Versions
substep.description: Each dataset version was stored as a serialized .pkl file using Python’s joblib module, ensuring fast read/write access during repeated model training and evaluation cycles.

step.name: Store datasets in interoperable tabular formats
step.description: Exported datasets in both .csv and .pkl formats; organized by variant set, model type, and training fold; archived to SURF Research Drive.

substep.name: Export to CSV and PKL
substep.description: Each version of the dataset—standardized features, training and test splits, and full integrated datasets—was exported as a .csv file and a binary .pkl file.

substep.name: Facilitate Data Inspection
substep.description: The .csv format allowed inspection and validation by collaborators, while the .pkl format supported efficient loading in Python-based machine learning pipelines.

substep.name: Version and Label Files
substep.description: All files were versioned, labeled by model configuration, and saved with unique identifiers that referenced the originating sequence set, ensuring traceability back to the structure prediction outputs.

substep.name: Store on Research Drive
substep.description: The datasets were stored on the project’s Research Drive under directory structures corresponding to variant set, model type, and training fold.
